Approach 3: Modified Binary Search (Standard Solution)
Intuition

Instead of checking only

nums[mid] == nums[left]

check

nums[left] == nums[mid] &&
nums[mid] == nums[right]

If all three are equal,

we cannot determine the sorted half.

Shrink both sides.

left++;
right--;

Then continue normal binary search.

This is the most commonly accepted interview solution.

Java
class Solution {
    public boolean search(int[] nums, int target) {

        int left = 0;
        int right = nums.length - 1;

        while (left <= right) {

            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] == target)
                return true;

            if (nums[left] == nums[mid] &&
                nums[mid] == nums[right]) {

                left++;
                right--;
            }

            else if (nums[left] <= nums[mid]) {

                if (nums[left] <= target &&
                    target < nums[mid]) {

                    right = mid - 1;

                } else {

                    left = mid + 1;
                }
            }

            else {

                if (nums[mid] < target &&
                    target <= nums[right]) {

                    left = mid + 1;

                } else {

                    right = mid - 1;
                }
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
Why Does Your Approach Work?

When

nums[mid] == nums[left]

we don't know which half is sorted.

Example

1 1 1 3 1
↑   ↑

Skipping one duplicate

left++;

removes ambiguity and allows binary search to continue.

Why Does the Standard Solution Shrink Both Ends?

Example

1 1 1 1 1

Here,

left == mid == right

Removing both ends

left++;
right--;

eliminates duplicates faster while preserving correctness.

